Energy Cabinet Secretary Charles Keter said the universal connectivity plan still remains on course as a matter of policy which is also provided for in the Energy Act 2019.Treasury, however, recently moved to re-introduce taxation on solar products used in setting up of the mini-grids, essentially throwing the plan in limbo. Ideally, every Kenyan household should have been connected to the national electricity grid by the end of next year, according to State ambitions. 

But this remains on paper as the country is set to miss its 2022 target leaving at least some two million households in the dark. 

With that, one of Jubilee administration’s key election pledges will have fallen apart and the ripple effects will not spare President Uhuru Kenyatta’s legacy under the Big Four Agenda of affordable housing, manufacturing, food security and universal healthcare. 



