Achievement of the country’s development goals under Vision 2030 of becoming a newly industrialised and middle-income nation may also experience a major setback since competitively-priced, reliable, safe and sustainable energy is a key driver to the achievement of the ambition. 






The Ministry of Energy now says the target is likely to be missed by about 15 percent owing to several factors among them slower rate of connectivity last year and increased taxation on solar products that may affect their use in far-flung rural areas. 

The estimate may, however, be conservative given that more households continue to emerge and there is an imminent slowdown in projects due to economic slowdown from Covid-19 and the charging political climate ahead of the 2022 elections. 

Energy Cabinet Secretary Charles Keter said the universal connectivity plan still remains on course as a matter of policy which is also provided for in the Energy Act 2019. 

Three million 

“We have done quite well over the period where we have pushed the number of connections to 7.8 million from below three million in 2013. We are likely to hit 85 percent by 2022 after we are done with the off-grid connection plan in the arid and semi-arid areas funded by the World Bank,” Mr Keter said. 



