The government through the Kenya National Electrification Strategy released in 2018 had aimed at connecting more than five million households to the main grid under a Sh270 billion plan that would see all households hooked to the electricity by 2022. 

The universal hook-up plan would be implemented in partnership with funding agencies such as the World Bank and the African Development Bank. 

It was the final leg in the increased electricity connection that had seen about 70 percent of households connected to the main grid. Data from Kenya Power shows connectivity growth rate has been slowing down over the years from a peak of 35.4 percent in 2015 when the government launched the Last Mile Connectivity Project to last year’s 4.5 percent when only 306,771 new customers were connected. 

Data submitted to the National Treasury by the Energy ministry shows that Kenya Power connected 1.2 million customers less in the three years to June 2020 due to a ‘reduced capital expenditure on the infrastructure development due KPLC Budget rationalisation.’ 



