The ministry had targeted giving priority to households located up to 15 kilometres within the existing Kenya Power lines in what is expected to yield 269,000 connections. Additional transformers in new areas would connect 2.7 million customers located between 600 metres and two kilometres around transformers. 

New transformers 

This may, however, not be possible since over the three-year period, Kenya Power fell short on the number of new transformers installed by 1,117, blaming the shortfall on non-availability of wooden poles. 

“Underachievement was due to budget cuts, delays in processing tax exemptions and clearance of materials at the port, government ban on logging, litigations, Covid 19 containment measures among others,” the ministry wrote regarding the missed target on the number of customers connected between June 2017 and June 2020. 

The explanations touching on the ban on logging, taxation and delayed clearance of materials at the port seemed to point inwards at the same government which may have shot itself in the foot in stifling one of Jubilee’s key pledges and legacy projects. 

In the same manner, the government had projected to take advantage of having some 121 mini grids facilitated to connect 35,000 customers to meet the ambitious target in remote areas. 



