Treasury, however, recently moved to re-introduce taxation on solar products used in setting up of the mini-grids, essentially throwing the plan in limbo. 

The country is also relying on solar to largely implement its Kenya Off-Grid Solar Access Project (KOSAP) financed by the World Bank, aimed at providing electricity to parts of the country that are not served by the national grid. 

Under the Sh15 billion project, counties of West Pokot, Turkana, Marsabit, Samburu, Isiolo, Mandera, Wajir, Garrisa, Tana River, Lamu, Kilifi, Kwale, Taita Taveta and Narok are expected to be connected to the electricity mains which the country considers a critical factor in fighting poverty. 



